#statement[
  A lightweight demo node to exercise wikilinks in statements and proofs.
]

#intuition[
  This is only here to make sure parsing and rendering work end to end.
]

#proof[
  We can cite a definition inline like [[def-group|basic group axioms]] and a theorem [[thm-pythagorean]] even if it's not listed in deps; the compiler should add it automatically.

  The proof text is otherwise vacuous, but it gives us nested formatting like *emphasis* and math $a^2 + b^2 = c^2$.
]

#statement[
  A small regression-test node to exercise wikilink rendering and auto-dependency capture from proofs.
]

#intuition[
  This theorem is intentionally trivial; its value is in linking to other nodes via Obsidian-style syntax.
]

#proof[
  We reference a base definition [[def-group|group axioms]] that is already in deps and a linked theorem [[thm-pythagorean]] that is not. The compiler should add the latter automatically when scanning proof blocks.

  Therefore, after compilation, this node should depend on both `def-group` and `thm-pythagorean` and render the links as clickable.
]

#statement[
  A group $G$ is cyclic if there exists an element $g in G$ such that $G = angle.l g angle.r$.
]

#intuition[
  A cyclic group is "unidimensional" in the sense that every single element can be reached just by repeating one specific generator.
]

#proof[
  This is a definition; no proof is required. However, for the atlas rigid block requirement, we note that the existence of such a generator defines the group structure.
]

#statement[
  Every bounded sequence in $RR^n$ has a convergent subsequence.
]

#intuition[
  If you have an infinite number of points trapped in a finite box, they have to "pile up" somewhere.
]

#proof[
  By the method of bisection. Since the sequence is bounded, it lies in a compact interval $[a, b]$. Subdivide the interval...
]
